<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06075233 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06075233 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; LOOKING FOR HELP -- Pepperdine's Rick Welch isguarded by Seton Hall's Terry Dehere in the Waves' 71-51 West Regional loss.Dehere scored a game-high 26 points.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  COLLEGE; BASKETBALL; GAME; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Shooting accuracy, or lack of it, has been New Mexico State's flaw all season.On Thursday, the flaw turned fatal as the 15th-ranked Aggies shot themselvesright out of the NCAA tournament.;    They made just 31 percent of theirfield-goal attempts, including 22 percent in the first half, as Creightonadvanced to the second round of the NCAA tournament for the first time since1974 with a 64-56 upset in a West Regional game in Salt Lake City.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  NEW MEXICO STATE CRUSHED BY COLD SHOOTING,CREIGHTON  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  NCAA TournamentWest  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;Virtually no one on the team had a good game,&quot; New Mexico State Coach NeilMcCarthy said. &quot;Everybody's below their average quite a bit. We're not a greatoutside shooting team, but generally we shoot the ball better.&quot;;    ChadGallagher, Creighton's 6-foot-10, 255-pound center, dominated the game earlyas the Bluejays took the lead and never lost it. Gallagher had 18 points and13 rebounds to lead the Missouri Valley Conference champions.;    &quot;I'm in afog,&quot; Creighton Coach Tony Barone said. &quot;We're one of 32 teams left in thecountry. That's a shock to me.&quot;; The Bluejays (24-7), the 11th seed in theWest, play 13th-ranked Seton Hall in Saturday's second round. New Mexico Statefinished 23-6.;  ARIZONA 93, ST. FRANCIS 80: Matt Othick scored a career-high25 points, 19 in the first half, as the eighth-ranked Wildcats outmanned theRed Flash.;    The junior guard made five three-pointers as the second-seededWildcats (27-6) used long-range shooting to take an early lead, then dominatedplay inside in the second half to advance to the second round for the fourthstraight year.;    The 15th-seeded Red Flash, the Northeastern Conferencechampion, was down by just nine points with 9 minutes, 21 seconds left.;   Othick, who broke his previous career high of 18 by halftime, led Arizona to a14-point lead at intermission.;  BRIGHAM YOUNG 61, VIRGINIA 48: Shawn Bradleybroke an NCAA tournament record with 10 blocked shots and the Cougars overcamea sloppy first half to oust the Cavaliers.;    Bradley, a 7-6 freshman, was anintimidating factor inside as BYU (21-12) held Virginia (21-12) to season lowsin points and field-goal percentage (28) before a highly partisan crowd at theUniversity of Utah campus arena.;    In addition to the 10 blocked shots,which broke the record of nine set by Navy's David Robinson in 1986, Bradleyforced Virginia to alter numerous other shots and generally created havocinside.;  SETON HALL 71, PEPPERDINE 51: Terry Dehere scored 26 points and theNo. 13 Pirates pulled away midway through the second half to trounce theWaves.;    Seton Hall gave away most of a 17-point first-half lead and led byonly two points early in the second half before going on a 26-6 run thatclinched the victory.;    Dehere capped the run by scoring the last sevenpoints of a 14-0 spurt as Seton Hall (23-8) put away the pesky Waves.;    Theloss snapped a 16-game winning streak for Pepperdine (22-9), which was playingwithout leading scorer Doug Christie, who tore cartilage in his knee in theWest Coast Conference tournament.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910315  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  566  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday March 15, 199100075233,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copy